{ [Source] Black's like, 'Okay, thank you very much. I'll take another pawn.' Right? { [%ai Fatal greed; black focuses on material while ignore the mating threats.] }
11. Ng5
{ [Source] Knight to G5. We're already in a winning position. We are about to checkmate them on H7. It's defended by the knight. Not for long, right? { [%ai Preparing the final blow by attacking the defender of h7.] }
11... h6 { { [%ai Trying to drive away the knight too late.] } 12. Rxf6
{ [Source] If they do something like this, thank you very much. We take it and when they take back, the game is over. { [%ai The final tactical sequence removes the defender and clinches the win.] }
12... exf6 { { [%ai Recapture is forced but unavailing.] } ) 2... Nc6
{ [Source] We're going to play F4. This is what starts the Grand Prix attack. You get these two pawns up. We're going to be pushing this guy forward later and attacking the king after it castles. }
3. f4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4
{ [Source] Bishop C4, lining up on the weak spot. That's a cool spot for the bishop to be. }
5... Bg7 6. O-O Nf6 7. d3
{ [Source] This is the critical main position of the Grand Prix attack. We've got both our knights out. We've got this F pawn pushed forward. We've got the bishop on C4 and then the pawn on D3 is defending. And we've castled. }
7... O-O 8. Qe1
{ [Source] Because our F pawn is pushed forward, we can very quickly slide the queen over and get to the king side to attack the king. That's very useful. }
8... a6 9. f5
{ [Source] We're going to push this pawn forward. It is not to recapture this pawn. We don't care. We're losing a pawn. We don't even care. When you play the Grand Prix attack, you have to get this idea into your mind. We don't mind if we lose pieces. We might lose some pawns along the way. We might lose some pieces along the way. Believe it or not, we might lose this rook along the way. That's okay because when you play the Grand Prix attack, you are going for the king. You are going for checkmate and that is all you care about. }
9... gxf5
{ [Source] We opened up our bishop. That's one thing. We open up the rook. That's another thing. And we've opened up black's king because when they take us, their king is more exposed. Also, it shuts down their bishop. }
10. Qh4
{ [Source] The queen comes over. Remember that's why we went here in the first place. We wanted to bring the queen over. And look at this. We are lining up on H7. }
10... fxe4
{ [Source] Black's like, 'Okay, thank you very much. I'll take another pawn.' }
11. Ng5
{ [Source] We're already in a winning position. We are about to checkmate them on H7. }
11... exd3 12. Rxf6
{ [Source] And you say, Nelson, it's defended by the knight. Not for long. If they do something like this, thank you very much. We take it. }
12... exf6 { [Source] And when they take back, the game is over. } 13. Qxh7#
{ [Source] This is 13 moves and the game is over with the beautiful checkmate on H7. This is what the Grand Prix attack is supposed to look like in a perfect world. { [%ai This is a tactical set-piece illustrating the attacking motifs. Black's moves (taking on f5 and e4) are common errors at the club level that facilitate White's kingside assault.] }
